body:
## 🐛 Bug Report

The Node.js and browser builds of exceljs have different behavior when exporting to CSV. The Node.js build works like I'd expect it to. In browser builds, however, the length of the first row limits the length of any subsequent rows. For example, if the first row has one column, then only one column is printed.

Lib version: 4.3.0

## Steps To Reproduce

```javascript
const nodeExceljs = require('exceljs');
const browserExceljs = require('exceljs/dist/exceljs.min');

async function writeSampleCsv(exceljs) {
  const workbook = new exceljs.Workbook();
  const worksheet = workbook.addWorksheet();

  worksheet.addRow(['Title']);
  worksheet.addRow(['A', 'B', 'C']);
  worksheet.addRow([1, 2, 3]);

  console.log((await workbook.csv.writeBuffer()).toString());
}

async function main() {
  console.log('Testing Node.js build');
  await writeSampleCsv(nodeExceljs);
  console.log();

  console.log('Testing browser build');
  await writeSampleCsv(browserExceljs);
}
main();
```

## The expected behaviour:

The two blocks of output should be identical. Instead, I get the following output:

```
Testing Node.js build
Title
A,B,C
1,2,3

Testing browser build
Title
A
1
```

comments.body:
I've noticed the same thing. A generic workaround I found is to do the following after adding all the data to the workbook. It basically just checks every cell of the first row up to the worksheet.columnCount and will set the value as an empty string if there currently isn't a value.

``` js
const workbook = new Workbook();
const worksheet = workbook.addWorksheet();

// populate worksheet with data

let firstRow = worksheet.getRow(1);

for (let i = 1; i <= worksheet.columnCount; i++) {
  let cell = firstRow.getCell(i);

  if (!cell.value) {
    cell.value = '';
  }
}
```

It seems hacky to have to do this, so hopefully this can be fixed.
